     </div> 
     <div class="mt-2 article-grid-container"> 
      <div class="article-grid-head"> 
       <div class="d-flex flex-items-baseline flex-justify-between mt-3"> 
        <h1 class="border-bottom-0">Webhook events and payloads</h1> 
        <div class="d-none d-lg-block ml-2"> <button class="btn-link Link--secondary js-print tooltipped tooltipped-n" aria-label="Print this article"> <!-- From https://heroicons.dev/ --> 
          <svg fill="none" height="18" width="18" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" viewbox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor">
           <path d="M17 17h2a2 2 0 002-2v-4a2 2 0 00-2-2H5a2 2 0 00-2 2v4a2 2 0 002 2h2m2 4h6a2 2 0 002-2v-4a2 2 0 00-2-2H9a2 2 0 00-2 2v4a2 2 0 002 2zm8-12V5a2 2 0 00-2-2H9a2 2 0 00-2 2v4h10z"></path>
          </svg> </button> 
        </div> 
       </div> 
       <div class="lead-mktg">
        <p>For each webhook event, you can review when the event occurs, an example payload, and descriptions about the payload object parameters.</p>
       </div> 
       <div class="product-callout border rounded-1 mb-4 p-3 color-border-success color-bg-success"> 
        <p>Enterprise accounts are available with GitHub Enterprise Cloud and GitHub Enterprise Server. For more information, see "<a href="/en/articles/about-enterprise-accounts">About enterprise accounts</a>." </p> 
        <p>Webhooks configured on enterprise accounts or organizations that are part of an enterprise account will include an <code>enterprise</code> account object.</p> 
       </div> 
      </div> 
      <div class="article-grid-toc border-bottom border-xl-0 pb-4 mb-5 pb-xl-0 mb-xl-0"> 
       <div class="article-grid-toc-content"> 
        <h2 id="in-this-article" class="f5 mb-2"><a class="Link--primary" href="#in-this-article">In this article</a></h2> 
        <ul class="list-style-none pl-0 f5 mb-0"> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-common-properties">Webhook payload object common properties</a></li>

         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#delete">delete</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#deploy_key">deploy_key</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#deployment">deployment</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#deployment_status">deployment_status</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#discussion">discussion</a></li>

         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#fork">fork</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#github_app_authorization">github_app_authorization</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#gollum">gollum</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#installation">installation</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#installation_repositories">installation_repositories</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#issue_comment">issue_comment</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#issues">issues</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#label">label</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#marketplace_purchase">marketplace_purchase</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#member">member</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#membership">membership</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#meta">meta</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#milestone">milestone</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#organization">organization</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#org_block">org_block</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#package">package</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#page_build">page_build</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#ping">ping</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#project_card">project_card</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#project_column">project_column</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#project">project</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#public">public</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#pull_request">pull_request</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#pull_request_review">pull_request_review</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#pull_request_review_comment">pull_request_review_comment</a></li>

         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#secret_scanning_alert">secret_scanning_alert</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#security_advisory">security_advisory</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#sponsorship">sponsorship</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#star">star</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#status">status</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#team">team</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#team_add">team_add</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#watch">watch</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#workflow_dispatch">workflow_dispatch</a></li> 
         <li class="ml-0  mb-2 lh-condensed"><a href="#workflow_run">workflow_run</a></li> 
        </ul> 
       </div> 
      </div> 
      <div id="article-contents" class="article-grid-body"> 
       <p>When configuring a webhook, you can use the UI or API to choose which events will send you payloads. Only subscribing to the specific events you plan on handling limits the number of HTTP requests to your server. You can also subscribe to all current and future events. By default, webhooks are only subscribed to the push event. You can change the list of subscribed events anytime.</p> 
       <p>You can create webhooks that subscribe to the events listed on this page. Each webhook event includes a description of the webhook properties and an example payload. For more information, see "<a href="/en/webhooks/creating">Creating webhooks</a>."</p> 
       <h3 id="webhook-payload-object-common-properties"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-common-properties">Webhook payload object common properties</a></h3> 
       <p>Each webhook event payload also contains properties unique to the event. You can find the unique properties in the individual event type sections.</p> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>action</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>Most webhook payloads contain an <code>action</code> property that contains the specific activity that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event. This property is included in every webhook payload.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repository</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#get-a-repository"><code>repository</code></a> where the event occurred. Webhook payloads contain the <code>repository</code> property when the event occurs from activity in a repository.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>organization</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>Webhook payloads contain the <a href="/en/rest/reference/orgs#get-an-organization"><code>organization</code></a> object when the webhook is configured for an organization or the event occurs from activity in a repository owned by an organization.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>installation</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The GitHub App installation. Webhook payloads contain the <code>installation</code> property when the event is configured for and sent to a GitHub App. For more information, see "<a href="/en/apps/building-github-apps">Building GitHub App</a>."</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table> 
       <p>The unique properties for a webhook event are the same properties you'll find in the <code>payload</code> property when using the <a href="/en/rest/reference/activity#events">Events API</a>. One exception is the <a href="#push"><code>push</code> event</a>. The unique properties of the <code>push</code> event webhook payload and the <code>payload</code> property in the Events API differ. The webhook payload contains more detailed information.</p> 
       <div class="extended-markdown tip border rounded-1 mb-4 p-3 color-border-info color-bg-info f5"> 
        <p><strong>Note:</strong> Payloads are capped at 25 MB. If your event generates a larger payload, a webhook will not be fired. This may happen, for example, on a <code>create</code> event if many branches or tags are pushed at once. We suggest monitoring your payload size to ensure delivery.</p> 
       </div> 
       <h4 id="delivery-headers"><a href="#delivery-headers">Delivery headers</a></h4> 
       <p>HTTP POST payloads that are delivered to your webhook's configured URL endpoint will contain several special headers:</p> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Header</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>X-GitHub-Event</code></td>
          <td>Name of the event that triggered the delivery.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>X-GitHub-Delivery</code></td>
          <td>A <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Globally_unique_identifier">GUID</a> to identify the delivery.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>X-Hub-Signature</code></td>
          <td>This header is sent if the webhook is configured with a <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#create-hook-config-params"><code>secret</code></a>. This is the HMAC hex digest of the request body, and is generated using the SHA-1 hash function and the <code>secret</code> as the HMAC <code>key</code>. <code>X-Hub-Signature</code> is provided for compatibility with existing integrations, and we recommend that you use the more secure <code>X-Hub-Signature-256</code> instead.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>X-Hub-Signature-256</code></td>
          <td>This header is sent if the webhook is configured with a <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#create-hook-config-params"><code>secret</code></a>. This is the HMAC hex digest of the request body, and is generated using the SHA-256 hash function and the <code>secret</code> as the HMAC <code>key</code>.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table> 
       <p>Also, the <code>User-Agent</code> for the requests will have the prefix <code>GitHub-Hookshot/</code>.</p> 
       <h4 id="example-delivery"><a href="#example-delivery">Example delivery</a></h4> 
       <pre><code class="hljs language-shell">&gt; POST /payload HTTP/2

&gt; Host: localhost:4567
&gt; X-GitHub-Delivery: 72d3162e-cc78-11e3-81ab-4c9367dc0958
&gt; X-Hub-Signature: sha1=7d38cdd689735b008b3c702edd92eea23791c5f6
&gt; X-Hub-Signature-256: sha256=d57c68ca6f92289e6987922ff26938930f6e66a2d161ef06abdf1859230aa23c
&gt; User-Agent: GitHub-Hookshot/044aadd
&gt; Content-Type: application/json
&gt; Content-Length: 6615
&gt; X-GitHub-Event: issues

&gt; {
&gt;   "action": "opened",
&gt;   "issue": {
&gt;     "url": "https://api.github.com/repos/octocat/Hello-World/issues/1347",
&gt;     "number": 1347,
&gt;     ...
&gt;   },
&gt;   "repository" : {
&gt;     "id": 1296269,
&gt;     "full_name": "octocat/Hello-World",
&gt;     "owner": {
&gt;       "login": "octocat",
&gt;       "id": 1,
&gt;       ...
&gt;     },
&gt;     ...
&gt;   },
&gt;   "sender": {
&gt;     "login": "octocat",
&gt;     "id": 1,
&gt;     ...
&gt;   }
&gt; }</code></pre> 
       <h3 id="check_run"><a href="#check_run">check_run</a></h3> 
       <p>Check run activity has occurred. The type of activity is specified in the <code>action</code> property of the payload object. For more information, see the "<a href="/en/rest/reference/checks#runs">check runs</a>" REST API.</p> 
       <div class="extended-markdown note border rounded-1 mb-4 p-3 color-border-info color-bg-info f5"> 
        <p><strong>Note:</strong> The Checks API only looks for pushes in the repository where the check suite or check run were created. Pushes to a branch in a forked repository are not detected and return an empty <code>pull_requests</code> array and a <code>null</code> value for <code>head_branch</code>.</p> 
       </div> 
       <h4 id="availability"><a href="#availability">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>Repository webhooks only receive payloads for the <code>created</code> and <code>completed</code> event types in a repository</li> 
        <li>Organization webhooks only receive payloads for the <code>created</code> and <code>completed</code> event types in repositories</li> 
        <li>GitHub Apps with the <code>checks:read</code> permission receive payloads for the <code>created</code> and <code>completed</code> events that occur in the repository where the app is installed. The app must have the <code>checks:write</code> permission to receive the <code>rerequested</code> and <code>requested_action</code> event types. The <code>rerequested</code> and <code>requested_action</code> event type payloads are only sent to the GitHub App being requested. GitHub Apps with the <code>checks:write</code> are automatically subscribed to this webhook event.</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object"><a href="#webhook-payload-object">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>action</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The action performed. Can be one of: 
           <ul>
            <li> <code>created</code> - A new check run was created.</li>
            <li> <code>completed</code> - The <code>status</code> of the check run is <code>completed</code>.</li>
            <li> <code>rerequested</code> - Someone requested to re-run your check run from the pull request UI. See "<a href="/en/articles/about-status-checks#checks">About status checks</a>" for more details about the GitHub UI. When you receive a <code>rerequested</code> action, you'll need to <a href="/en/rest/reference/checks#create-a-check-run">create a new check run</a>. Only the GitHub App that someone requests to re-run the check will receive the <code>rerequested</code> payload.</li>
            <li> <code>requested_action</code> - Someone requested an action your app provides to be taken. Only the GitHub App someone requests to perform an action will receive the <code>requested_action</code> payload. To learn more about check runs and requested actions, see "<a href="/en/rest/reference/checks#check-runs-and-requested-actions">Check runs and requested actions</a>."</li>
           </ul></td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>check_run</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/checks#get-a-check-run">check_run</a>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>check_run[status]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The current status of the check run. Can be <code>queued</code>, <code>in_progress</code>, or <code>completed</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>check_run[conclusion]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The result of the completed check run. Can be one of <code>success</code>, <code>failure</code>, <code>neutral</code>, <code>cancelled</code>, <code>timed_out</code>, <code>action_required</code> or <code>stale</code>. This value will be <code>null</code> until the check run has <code>completed</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>check_run[name]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The name of the check run.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>check_run[check_suite][id]</code></td>
          <td><code>integer</code></td>
          <td>The id of the check suite that this check run is part of.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>check_run[check_suite][pull_requests]</code></td>
          <td><code>array</code></td>
          <td>An array of pull requests that match this check suite. A pull request matches a check suite if they have the same <code>head_sha</code> and <code>head_branch</code>. When the check suite's <code>head_branch</code> is in a forked repository it will be <code>null</code> and the <code>pull_requests</code> array will be empty.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>check_run[check_suite][deployment]</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>A deployment to a repository environment. This will only be populated if the check run was created by a GitHub Actions workflow job that references an environment.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>requested_action</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The action requested by the user.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>requested_action[identifier]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The integrator reference of the action requested by the user.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repository</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#get-a-repository"><code>repository</code></a> where the event occurred.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>organization</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>Webhook payloads contain the <a href="/en/rest/reference/orgs#get-an-organization"><code>organization</code></a> object when the webhook is configured for an organization or the event occurs from activity in a repository owned by an organization.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>installation</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The GitHub App installation. Webhook payloads contain the <code>installation</code> property when the event is configured for and sent to a GitHub App.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table>

       <h3 id="check_suite"><a href="#check_suite">check_suite</a></h3> 
       <p>Check suite activity has occurred. The type of activity is specified in the <code>action</code> property of the payload object. For more information, see the "<a href="/en/rest/reference/checks#suites">check suites</a>" REST API.</p> 
       <div class="extended-markdown note border rounded-1 mb-4 p-3 color-border-info color-bg-info f5"> 
        <p><strong>Note:</strong> The Checks API only looks for pushes in the repository where the check suite or check run were created. Pushes to a branch in a forked repository are not detected and return an empty <code>pull_requests</code> array and a <code>null</code> value for <code>head_branch</code>.</p> 
       </div> 
       <h4 id="availability-1"><a href="#availability-1">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>Repository webhooks only receive payloads for the <code>completed</code> event types in a repository</li> 
        <li>Organization webhooks only receive payloads for the <code>completed</code> event types in repositories</li> 
        <li>GitHub Apps with the <code>checks:read</code> permission receive payloads for the <code>created</code> and <code>completed</code> events that occur in the repository where the app is installed. The app must have the <code>checks:write</code> permission to receive the <code>requested</code> and <code>rerequested</code> event types. The <code>requested</code> and <code>rerequested</code> event type payloads are only sent to the GitHub App being requested. GitHub Apps with the <code>checks:write</code> are automatically subscribed to this webhook event.</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object-1"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-1">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>action</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The action performed. Can be:
           <ul>
            <li><code>completed</code> - All check runs in a check suite have completed.</li>
            <li><code>requested</code> - Occurs when new code is pushed to the app's repository. When you receive the <code>requested</code> action events, you'll need to <a href="/en/rest/reference/checks#create-a-check-run">create a new check run</a>.</li>
            <li><code>rerequested</code> - Occurs when someone requests to re-run the entire check suite from the pull request UI. When you receive the <code>rerequested</code> action events, you'll need to <a href="/en/rest/reference/checks#create-a-check-run">create a new check run</a>. See "<a href="/en/articles/about-status-checks#checks">About status checks</a>" for more details about the GitHub UI.</li>
           </ul></td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>check_suite</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/checks#suites">check_suite</a>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>check_suite[head_branch]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The head branch name the changes are on.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>check_suite[head_sha]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The SHA of the most recent commit for this check suite.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>check_suite[status]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The summary status for all check runs that are part of the check suite. Can be <code>requested</code>, <code>in_progress</code>, or <code>completed</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>check_suite[conclusion]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The summary conclusion for all check runs that are part of the check suite. Can be one of <code>success</code>, <code>failure</code>, <code>neutral</code>, <code>cancelled</code>, <code>timed_out</code>, <code>action_required</code> or <code>stale</code>. This value will be <code>null</code> until the check run has <code>completed</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>check_suite[url]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>URL that points to the check suite API resource.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>check_suite[pull_requests]</code></td>
          <td><code>array</code></td>
          <td>An array of pull requests that match this check suite. A pull request matches a check suite if they have the same <code>head_sha</code> and <code>head_branch</code>. When the check suite's <code>head_branch</code> is in a forked repository it will be <code>null</code> and the <code>pull_requests</code> array will be empty.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repository</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#get-a-repository"><code>repository</code></a> where the event occurred.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>organization</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>Webhook payloads contain the <a href="/en/rest/reference/orgs#get-an-organization"><code>organization</code></a> object when the webhook is configured for an organization or the event occurs from activity in a repository owned by an organization.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>installation</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The GitHub App installation. Webhook payloads contain the <code>installation</code> property when the event is configured for and sent to a GitHub App.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-example-1"><a href="#webhook-payload-example-1">Webhook payload example</a></h4> 
       <div class="height-constrained-code-block"> 
        <pre><code class="hljs language-json">{
  <span class="hljs-attr">"action"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"completed"</span>,
  <span class="hljs-attr">"check_suite"</span>: {
    <span class="hljs-attr">"id"</span>: <span class="hljs-number">118578147</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"node_id"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"MDEwOkNoZWNrU3VpdGUxMTg1NzgxNDc="</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"head_branch"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"changes"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"head_sha"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"ec26c3e57ca3a959ca5aad62de7213c562f8c821"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"status"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"completed"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"conclusion"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"success"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/repos/Codertocat/Hello-World/check-suites/118578147"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"before"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"6113728f27ae82c7b1a177c8d03f9e96e0adf246"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"after"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"ec26c3e57ca3a959ca5aad62de7213c562f8c821"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"pull_requests"</span>: [
      {
        <span class="hljs-attr">"url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/repos/Codertocat/Hello-World/pulls/2"</span>,
        <span class="hljs-attr">"id"</span>: <span class="hljs-number">279147437</span>,
        <span class="hljs-attr">"number"</span>: <span class="hljs-number">2</span>,
        <span class="hljs-attr">"head"</span>: {
          <span class="hljs-attr">"ref"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"changes"</span>,
          <span class="hljs-attr">"sha"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"ec26c3e57ca3a959ca5aad62de7213c562f8c821"</span>,
          <span class="hljs-attr">"repo"</span>: {
            <span class="hljs-attr">"id"</span>: <span class="hljs-number">186853002</span>,
            <span class="hljs-attr">"url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/repos/Codertocat/Hello-World"</span>,
            <span class="hljs-attr">"name"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"Hello-World"</span>
          }

       </div> 
       <h3 id="code_scanning_alert"><a href="#code_scanning_alert">code_scanning_alert</a></h3> 
       <p>Activity related to code scanning alerts in a repository. The type of activity is specified in the action property of the payload object. For more information, see <a href="/en/github/finding-security-vulnerabilities-and-errors-in-your-code/about-code-scanning">About code scanning</a>.</p> 
       <h4 id="availability-2"><a href="#availability-2">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>Repository webhooks</li> 
        <li>Organization webhooks</li> 
        <li>GitHub Apps with the <code>security_events :read</code> permission</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object-2"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-2">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>action</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The action that was performed. This can be one of <code>created</code>, <code>reopened_by_user</code>, <code>closed_by_user</code>, <code>fixed</code>, <code>appeared_in_branch</code>, or <code>reopened</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>alert</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The code scanning alert involved in the event.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>ref</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The Git reference of the code scanning alert. When the action is <code>reopened_by_user</code> or <code>closed_by_user</code>, the event was triggered by the <code>sender</code> and this value will be empty.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>commit_oid</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The commit SHA of the code scanning alert. When the action is <code>reopened_by_user</code> or <code>closed_by_user</code>, the event was triggered by the <code>sender</code> and this value will be empty.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repository</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#get-a-repository"><code>repository</code></a> where the event occurred.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>organization</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>Webhook payloads contain the <a href="/en/rest/reference/orgs#get-an-organization"><code>organization</code></a> object when the webhook is configured for an organization or the event occurs from activity in a repository owned by an organization.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>installation</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The GitHub App installation. Webhook payloads contain the <code>installation</code> property when the event is configured for and sent to a GitHub App.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>If the <code>action</code> is <code>reopened_by_user</code> or <code>closed_by_user</code>, the <code>sender</code> object will be the user that triggered the event. The <code>sender</code> object is <code>github</code> for all other actions.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table>

       </div> 
       <h3 id="commit_comment"><a href="#commit_comment">commit_comment</a></h3> 
       <p>A commit comment is created. The type of activity is specified in the <code>action</code> property of the payload object. For more information, see the "<a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#comments">commit comment</a>" REST API.</p> 
       <h4 id="availability-3"><a href="#availability-3">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>Repository webhooks</li> 
        <li>Organization webhooks</li> 
        <li>GitHub Apps with the <code>contents</code> permission</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object-3"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-3">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>action</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The action performed. Can be <code>created</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>comment</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#get-a-commit-comment">commit comment</a> resource.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repository</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#get-a-repository"><code>repository</code></a> where the event occurred.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>organization</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>Webhook payloads contain the <a href="/en/rest/reference/orgs#get-an-organization"><code>organization</code></a> object when the webhook is configured for an organization or the event occurs from activity in a repository owned by an organization.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>installation</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The GitHub App installation. Webhook payloads contain the <code>installation</code> property when the event is configured for and sent to a GitHub App.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-example-3"><a href="#webhook-payload-example-3">Webhook payload example</a></h4> 
       <div class="height-constrained-code-block"> 
        <pre><code class="hljs language-json">{
  <span class="hljs-attr">"action"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"created"</span>,
  <span class="hljs-attr">"comment"</span>: {
    <span class="hljs-attr">"url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/repos/Codertocat/Hello-World/comments/33548674"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"html_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://github.com/Codertocat/Hello-World/commit/6113728f27ae82c7b1a177c8d03f9e96e0adf246#commitcomment-33548674"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"id"</span>: <span class="hljs-number">33548674</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"node_id"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"MDEzOkNvbW1pdENvbW1lbnQzMzU0ODY3NA=="</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"user"</span>: {
      <span class="hljs-attr">"login"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"Codertocat"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"id"</span>: <span class="hljs-number">21031067</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"node_id"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"MDQ6VXNlcjIxMDMxMDY3"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"avatar_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://avatars1.githubusercontent.com/u/21031067?v=4"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"gravatar_id"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">""</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/Codertocat"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"html_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://github.com/Codertocat"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"followers_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/Codertocat/followers"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"following_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/Codertocat/following{/other_user}"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"gists_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/Codertocat/gists{/gist_id}"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"starred_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/Codertocat/starred{/owner}{/repo}"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"subscriptions_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/Codertocat/subscriptions"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"organizations_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/Codertocat/orgs"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"repos_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/Codertocat/repos"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"events_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/Codertocat/events{/privacy}"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"received_events_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/Codertocat/received_events"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"type"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"User"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"site_admin"</span>: <span class="hljs-literal">false</span>
    },

       <h3 id="content_reference"><a href="#content_reference">content_reference</a></h3> 
       <p>A new content reference is <code>created</code>. A new content reference is created when the body or comment of an issue or pull request includes a URL that matches a configured content reference domain. For more information, see "<a href="/en/apps/using-content-attachments">Using content attachments</a>" to learn more about content references and attachments.</p> 
       <p>Webhook events are triggered based on the specificity of the domain you register. For example, if you register a subdomain (<code>https://subdomain.example.com</code>) then only URLs for the subdomain trigger this event. If you register a domain (<code>https://example.com</code>) then URLs for domain and all subdomains trigger this event. See "<a href="/en/rest/reference/apps#create-a-content-attachment">Create a content attachment</a>" to create a new content attachment.</p> 
       <h4 id="availability-4"><a href="#availability-4">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>GitHub Apps with the <code>content_references:write</code> permission</li> 
       </ul>

</code></pre> 
       </div> 
       <h3 id="create"><a href="#create">create</a></h3> 
       <p>A Git branch or tag is created. For more information, see the "<a href="/en/rest/reference/git">Git data</a>" REST API.</p> 
       <div class="extended-markdown note border rounded-1 mb-4 p-3 color-border-info color-bg-info f5"> 
        <p><strong>Note:</strong> You will not receive a webhook for this event when you push more than three tags at once.</p> 
       </div> 
       <h4 id="availability-5"><a href="#availability-5">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>Repository webhooks</li> 
        <li>Organization webhooks</li> 
        <li>GitHub Apps with the <code>contents</code> permission</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object-4"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-4">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>ref</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/git#get-a-reference"><code>git ref</code></a> resource.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>ref_type</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The type of Git ref object created in the repository. Can be either <code>branch</code> or <code>tag</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>master_branch</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The name of the repository's default branch (usually <code>main</code>).</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>description</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The repository's current description.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>pusher_type</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The pusher type for the event. Can be either <code>user</code> or a deploy key.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repository</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#get-a-repository"><code>repository</code></a> where the event occurred.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>organization</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>Webhook payloads contain the <a href="/en/rest/reference/orgs#get-an-organization"><code>organization</code></a> object when the webhook is configured for an organization or the event occurs from activity in a repository owned by an organization.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>installation</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The GitHub App installation. Webhook payloads contain the <code>installation</code> property when the event is configured for and sent to a GitHub App.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table>

    <span class="hljs-attr">"organizations_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/Codertocat/orgs"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"repos_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/Codertocat/repos"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"events_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/Codertocat/events{/privacy}"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"received_events_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/Codertocat/received_events"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"type"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"User"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"site_admin"</span>: <span class="hljs-literal">false</span>
  }
}
</code></pre> 
       </div> 
       <h3 id="delete"><a href="#delete">delete</a></h3> 
       <p>A Git branch or tag is deleted. For more information, see the "<a href="/en/rest/reference/git">Git data</a>" REST API.</p> 
       <div class="extended-markdown note border rounded-1 mb-4 p-3 color-border-info color-bg-info f5"> 
        <p><strong>Note:</strong> You will not receive a webhook for this event when you delete more than three tags at once.</p> 
       </div> 
       <h4 id="availability-6"><a href="#availability-6">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>Repository webhooks</li> 
        <li>Organization webhooks</li> 
        <li>GitHub Apps with the <code>contents</code> permission</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object-5"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-5">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>ref</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/git#get-a-reference"><code>git ref</code></a> resource.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>ref_type</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The type of Git ref oject deleted in the repository. Can be <code>branch</code> or <code>tag</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>pusher_type</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The pusher type for the event. Can be either <code>user</code> or a deploy key.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repository</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#get-a-repository"><code>repository</code></a> where the event occurred.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>organization</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>Webhook payloads contain the <a href="/en/rest/reference/orgs#get-an-organization"><code>organization</code></a> object when the webhook is configured for an organization or the event occurs from activity in a repository owned by an organization.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>installation</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The GitHub App installation. Webhook payloads contain the <code>installation</code> property when the event is configured for and sent to a GitHub App.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-example-6"><a href="#webhook-payload-example-6">Webhook payload example</a></h4>

       <h3 id="deploy_key"><a href="#deploy_key">deploy_key</a></h3> 
       <p>A deploy key is added or removed from a repository. The type of activity is specified in the <code>action</code> property of the payload object. For more information, see the "<a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#keys">Deploy keys</a>" REST API.</p> 
       <h4 id="availability-7"><a href="#availability-7">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>Repository webhooks</li> 
        <li>Organization webhooks</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object-6"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-6">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>action</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The action performed. Can be either <code>created</code> or <code>deleted</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>key</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#get-a-deploy-key"><code>deploy key</code></a> resource.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repository</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#get-a-repository"><code>repository</code></a> where the event occurred.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>organization</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>Webhook payloads contain the <a href="/en/rest/reference/orgs#get-an-organization"><code>organization</code></a> object when the webhook is configured for an organization or the event occurs from activity in a repository owned by an organization.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-example-7"><a href="#webhook-payload-example-7">Webhook payload example</a></h4> 
       <div class="height-constrained-code-block"> 
        <pre><code class="hljs language-json">{
  <span class="hljs-attr">"action"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"created"</span>,

      <span class="hljs-attr">"gravatar_id"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">""</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/Codertocat"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"html_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://github.com/Codertocat"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"followers_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/Codertocat/followers"</span>,

    <span class="hljs-attr">"html_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://github.com/Codertocat/Hello-World"</span>,

       </div> 
       <h3 id="deployment"><a href="#deployment">deployment</a></h3> 
       <p>A deployment is created. The type of activity is specified in the <code>action</code> property of the payload object. For more information, see the "<a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#list-deployments">deployment</a>" REST API.</p> 
       <h4 id="availability-8"><a href="#availability-8">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>Repository webhooks</li> 
        <li>Organization webhooks</li> 
        <li>GitHub Apps with the <code>deployments</code> permission</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object-7"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-7">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>action</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The action performed. Can be <code>created</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>deployment</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#list-deployments">deployment</a>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repository</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#get-a-repository"><code>repository</code></a> where the event occurred.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>organization</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>Webhook payloads contain the <a href="/en/rest/reference/orgs#get-an-organization"><code>organization</code></a> object when the webhook is configured for an organization or the event occurs from activity in a repository owned by an organization.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>installation</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The GitHub App installation. Webhook payloads contain the <code>installation</code> property when the event is configured for and sent to a GitHub App.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table>

</code></pre> 
       </div> 
       <h3 id="deployment_status"><a href="#deployment_status">deployment_status</a></h3> 
       <p>A deployment is created. The type of activity is specified in the <code>action</code> property of the payload object. For more information, see the "<a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#list-deployment-statuses">deployment statuses</a>" REST API.</p> 
       <h4 id="availability-9"><a href="#availability-9">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>Repository webhooks</li> 
        <li>Organization webhooks</li> 
        <li>GitHub Apps with the <code>deployments</code> permission</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object-8"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-8">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>action</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The action performed. Can be <code>created</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>deployment_status</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#list-deployment-statuses">deployment status</a>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>deployment_status["state"]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The new state. Can be <code>pending</code>, <code>success</code>, <code>failure</code>, or <code>error</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>deployment_status["target_url"]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The optional link added to the status.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>deployment_status["description"]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The optional human-readable description added to the status.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>deployment</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#list-deployments">deployment</a> that this status is associated with.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repository</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#get-a-repository"><code>repository</code></a> where the event occurred.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>organization</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>Webhook payloads contain the <a href="/en/rest/reference/orgs#get-an-organization"><code>organization</code></a> object when the webhook is configured for an organization or the event occurs from activity in a repository owned by an organization.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>installation</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The GitHub App installation. Webhook payloads contain the <code>installation</code> property when the event is configured for and sent to a GitHub App.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table>

       </div> 
       <h3 id="discussion"><a href="#discussion">discussion</a></h3> 
       <div class="extended-markdown note border rounded-1 mb-4 p-3 color-border-info color-bg-info f5"> 
        <p><strong>Note:</strong> Webhook events for GitHub Discussions are currently in beta and subject to change.</p> 
       </div> 
       <p>Activity related to a discussion. For more information, see the "<a href="/en/graphql/guides/using-the-graphql-api-for-discussions">Using the GraphQL API for discussions</a>."</p> 
       <h4 id="availability-10"><a href="#availability-10">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>Repository webhooks</li> 
        <li>Organization webhooks</li> 
        <li>GitHub Apps with the <code>discussions</code> permission</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object-9"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-9">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>action</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The action performed. Can be <code>created</code>, <code>edited</code>, <code>deleted</code>, <code>pinned</code>, <code>unpinned</code>, <code>locked</code>, <code>unlocked</code>, <code>transferred</code>, <code>category_changed</code>, <code>answered</code>, or <code>unanswered</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>discussion</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/graphql/guides/using-the-graphql-api-for-discussions#discussion"><code>discussion</code></a> resource.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repository</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/graphql/reference/objects#repository"><code>repository</code></a> where the event occurred.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>organization</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>Webhook payloads contain the <a href="/en/graphql/reference/objects#organization"><code>organization</code></a> object when the webhook is configured for an organization or the event occurs from activity in a repository owned by an organization.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-example-10"><a href="#webhook-payload-example-10">Webhook payload example</a></h4> 
       <div class="height-constrained-code-block">

       </div> 
       <h3 id="discussion_comment"><a href="#discussion_comment">discussion_comment</a></h3> 
       <div class="extended-markdown note border rounded-1 mb-4 p-3 color-border-info color-bg-info f5"> 
        <p><strong>Note:</strong> Webhook events for GitHub Discussions are currently in beta and subject to change.</p> 
       </div> 
       <p>Activity related to a comment in a discussion. For more information, see "<a href="/en/graphql/guides/using-the-graphql-api-for-discussions">Using the GraphQL API for discussions</a>."</p> 
       <h4 id="availability-11"><a href="#availability-11">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>Repository webhooks</li> 
        <li>Organization webhooks</li> 
        <li>GitHub Apps with the <code>discussions</code> permission</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object-10"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-10">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>action</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The action performed. Can be <code>created</code>, <code>edited</code>, or <code>deleted</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>comment</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/graphql/guides/using-the-graphql-api-for-discussions#discussioncomment"><code>discussion comment</code></a> resource.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>discussion</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/graphql/guides/using-the-graphql-api-for-discussions#discussion"><code>discussion</code></a> resource.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repository</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/graphql/reference/objects#repository"><code>repository</code></a> where the event occurred.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>organization</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>Webhook payloads contain the <a href="/en/graphql/reference/objects#organization"><code>organization</code></a> object when the webhook is configured for an organization or the event occurs from activity in a repository owned by an organization.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-example-11"><a href="#webhook-payload-example-11">Webhook payload example</a></h4>

       <h3 id="fork"><a href="#fork">fork</a></h3> 
       <p>A user forks a repository. For more information, see the "<a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#forks">forks</a>" REST API.</p> 
       <h4 id="availability-12"><a href="#availability-12">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>Repository webhooks</li> 
        <li>Organization webhooks</li> 
        <li>GitHub Apps with the <code>contents</code> permission</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object-11"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-11">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>forkee</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The created <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#get-a-repository"><code>repository</code></a> resource.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repository</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#get-a-repository"><code>repository</code></a> where the event occurred.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>organization</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>Webhook payloads contain the <a href="/en/rest/reference/orgs#get-an-organization"><code>organization</code></a> object when the webhook is configured for an organization or the event occurs from activity in a repository owned by an organization.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>installation</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The GitHub App installation. Webhook payloads contain the <code>installation</code> property when the event is configured for and sent to a GitHub App.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-example-12"><a href="#webhook-payload-example-12">Webhook payload example</a></h4>

       <h3 id="github_app_authorization"><a href="#github_app_authorization">github_app_authorization</a></h3> 
       <p>When someone revokes their authorization of a GitHub App, this event occurs. A GitHub App receives this webhook by default and cannot unsubscribe from this event.</p> 
       <p>Anyone can revoke their authorization of a GitHub App from their <a href="https://github.com/settings/apps/authorizations">GitHub account settings page</a>. Revoking the authorization of a GitHub App does not uninstall the GitHub App. You should program your GitHub App so that when it receives this webhook, it stops calling the API on behalf of the person who revoked the token. If your GitHub App continues to use a revoked access token, it will receive the <code>401 Bad Credentials</code> error. For details about user-to-server requests, which require GitHub App authorization, see "<a href="/en/apps/building-github-apps/identifying-and-authorizing-users-for-github-apps">Identifying and authorizing users for GitHub Apps</a>."</p> 
       <h4 id="availability-13"><a href="#availability-13">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>GitHub Apps</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object-12"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-12">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>action</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The action performed. Can be <code>revoked</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-example-13"><a href="#webhook-payload-example-13">Webhook payload example</a></h4> 
       <div class="height-constrained-code-block"> 
        <pre><code class="hljs language-json">{
  <span class="hljs-attr">"action"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"revoked"</span>,
  <span class="hljs-attr">"sender"</span>: {
    <span class="hljs-attr">"login"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"octocat"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"id"</span>: <span class="hljs-number">1</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"node_id"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"MDQ6VXNlcjIxMDMxMDY3"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"avatar_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://github.com/images/error/octocat_happy.gif"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"gravatar_id"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">""</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/octocat"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"html_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://github.com/octocat"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"followers_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/octocat/followers"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"following_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/octocat/following{/other_user}"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"gists_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/octocat/gists{/gist_id}"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"starred_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/octocat/starred{/owner}{/repo}"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"subscriptions_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/octocat/subscriptions"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"organizations_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/octocat/orgs"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"repos_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/octocat/repos"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"events_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/octocat/events{/privacy}"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"received_events_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://api.github.com/users/octocat/received_events"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"type"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"User"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"site_admin"</span>: <span class="hljs-literal">false</span>
  }
}
</code></pre> 
       </div> 
       <h3 id="gollum"><a href="#gollum">gollum</a></h3> 
       <p>A wiki page is created or updated. For more information, see the "<a href="/en/communities/documenting-your-project-with-wikis/about-wikis">About wikis</a>".</p> 
       <h4 id="availability-14"><a href="#availability-14">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>Repository webhooks</li> 
        <li>Organization webhooks</li> 
        <li>GitHub Apps with the <code>contents</code> permission</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object-13"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-13">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>pages</code></td>
          <td><code>array</code></td>
          <td>The pages that were updated.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>pages[][page_name]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The name of the page.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>pages[][title]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The current page title.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>pages[][action]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The action that was performed on the page. Can be <code>created</code> or <code>edited</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>pages[][sha]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The latest commit SHA of the page.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>pages[][html_url]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>Points to the HTML wiki page.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repository</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#get-a-repository"><code>repository</code></a> where the event occurred.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>organization</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>Webhook payloads contain the <a href="/en/rest/reference/orgs#get-an-organization"><code>organization</code></a> object when the webhook is configured for an organization or the event occurs from activity in a repository owned by an organization.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>installation</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The GitHub App installation. Webhook payloads contain the <code>installation</code> property when the event is configured for and sent to a GitHub App.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-example-14"><a href="#webhook-payload-example-14">Webhook payload example</a></h4> 
       <div class="height-constrained-code-block"> 
        <pre><code class="hljs language-json">{
  <span class="hljs-attr">"pages"</span>: [
    {
      <span class="hljs-attr">"page_name"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"Home"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"title"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"Home"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"summary"</span>: <span class="hljs-literal">null</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"action"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"edited"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"sha"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"6bf911d3801dd1ef957fc6ade5a8d96429e7fa39"</span>,
      <span class="hljs-attr">"html_url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"https://github.com/Codertocat/Hello-World/wiki/Home"</span>
    }
  ],
  <span class="hljs-attr">"repository"</span>: {
    <span class="hljs-attr">"id"</span>: <span class="hljs-number">186853002</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"node_id"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"MDEwOlJlcG9zaXRvcnkxODY4NTMwMDI="</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"name"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"Hello-World"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"full_name"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"Codertocat/Hello-World"</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"private"</span>: <span class="hljs-literal">false</span>,
    <span class="hljs-attr">"owner"</span>: {
      <span class="hljs-attr">"login"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">"Codertocat"</span>,

       <h3 id="installation"><a href="#installation">installation</a></h3> 
       <p>Activity related to a GitHub App installation. The type of activity is specified in the <code>action</code> property of the payload object. For more information, see the "<a href="/en/rest/reference/apps">GitHub App installation</a>" REST API.</p> 
       <div class="extended-markdown note border rounded-1 mb-4 p-3 color-border-info color-bg-info f5"> 
        <p><strong>Note:</strong> This event replaces the deprecated <code>integration_installation</code> event. </p> 
       </div> 
       <h4 id="availability-15"><a href="#availability-15">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>GitHub Apps</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object-14"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-14">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>action</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The action that was performed. Can be one of:
           <ul>
            <li><code>created</code> - Someone installs a GitHub App.</li>
            <li><code>deleted</code> - Someone uninstalls a GitHub App</li>
            <li><code>suspend</code> - Someone suspends a GitHub App installation.</li>
            <li><code>unsuspend</code> - Someone unsuspends a GitHub App installation.</li>
            <li><code>new_permissions_accepted</code> - Someone accepts new permissions for a GitHub App installation. When a GitHub App owner requests new permissions, the person who installed the GitHub App must accept the new permissions request. </li>
           </ul></td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repositories</code></td>
          <td><code>array</code></td>
          <td>An array of repository objects that the installation can access.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>installation</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The GitHub App installation.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-example-15"><a href="#webhook-payload-example-15">Webhook payload example</a></h4> 
       <div class="height-constrained-code-block">

       </div> 
       <h3 id="installation_repositories"><a href="#installation_repositories">installation_repositories</a></h3> 
       <p>Activity related to repositories being added to a GitHub App installation. The type of activity is specified in the <code>action</code> property of the payload object. For more information, see the "<a href="/en/rest/reference/apps">GitHub App installation</a>" REST API.</p> 
       <div class="extended-markdown note border rounded-1 mb-4 p-3 color-border-info color-bg-info f5"> 
        <p><strong>Note:</strong> This event replaces the deprecated <code>integration_installation_repositories</code> event.</p> 
       </div> 
       <h4 id="availability-16"><a href="#availability-16">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>GitHub Apps</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object-15"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-15">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>action</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The action that was performed. Can be either <code>added</code> or <code>removed</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repository_selection</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The choice of repositories the installation is on. Can be either <code>selected</code> or <code>all</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repositories_added</code></td>
          <td><code>array</code></td>
          <td>An array of repository objects, which were added to the installation.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repositories_removed</code></td>
          <td><code>array</code></td>
          <td>An array of repository objects, which were removed from the installation.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>installation</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The GitHub App installation.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-example-16"><a href="#webhook-payload-example-16">Webhook payload example</a></h4>

       </div> 
       <h3 id="issue_comment"><a href="#issue_comment">issue_comment</a></h3> 
       <p>Activity related to an issue or pull request comment. The type of activity is specified in the <code>action</code> property of the payload object. For more information, see the "<a href="/en/rest/reference/issues#comments">issue comments</a>" REST API.</p> 
       <h4 id="availability-17"><a href="#availability-17">Availability</a></h4> 
       <ul> 
        <li>Repository webhooks</li> 
        <li>Organization webhooks</li> 
        <li>GitHub Apps with the <code>issues</code> permission</li> 
       </ul> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-object-16"><a href="#webhook-payload-object-16">Webhook payload object</a></h4> 
       <table>
        <thead>
         <tr>
          <th>Key</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Description</th>
         </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
         <tr>
          <td><code>action</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The action that was performed on the comment. Can be one of <code>created</code>, <code>edited</code>, or <code>deleted</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>changes</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The changes to the comment if the action was <code>edited</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>changes[body][from]</code></td>
          <td><code>string</code></td>
          <td>The previous version of the body if the action was <code>edited</code>.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>issue</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/issues">issue</a> the comment belongs to.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>comment</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/issues#comments">comment</a> itself.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>repository</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The <a href="/en/rest/reference/repos#get-a-repository"><code>repository</code></a> where the event occurred.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>organization</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>Webhook payloads contain the <a href="/en/rest/reference/orgs#get-an-organization"><code>organization</code></a> object when the webhook is configured for an organization or the event occurs from activity in a repository owned by an organization.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>installation</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The GitHub App installation. Webhook payloads contain the <code>installation</code> property when the event is configured for and sent to a GitHub App.</td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
          <td><code>sender</code></td>
          <td><code>object</code></td>
          <td>The user that triggered the event.</td>
         </tr>
        </tbody>
       </table> 
       <h4 id="webhook-payload-example-17"><a href="#webhook-payload-example-17">Webhook payload example</a></h4> 
       <div class="height-constrained-code-block">
